<Link id="l00055" /><CodeLine lineNumber="55"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00056" /><CodeLine lineNumber="56"><Highlight kind="comment">/// A self-contained host- and target-independent arbitrary-precision</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00057" /><CodeLine lineNumber="57"><Highlight kind="comment">/// floating-point software implementation.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00058" /><CodeLine lineNumber="58"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00059" /><CodeLine lineNumber="59"><Highlight kind="comment">/// APFloat uses bignum integer arithmetic as provided by static functions in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00060" /><CodeLine lineNumber="60"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the APInt class.  The library will work with bignum integers whose parts are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00061" /><CodeLine lineNumber="61"><Highlight kind="comment">/// any unsigned type at least 16 bits wide, but 64 bits is recommended.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00062" /><CodeLine lineNumber="62"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00063" /><CodeLine lineNumber="63"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Written for clarity rather than speed, in particular with a view to use in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00064" /><CodeLine lineNumber="64"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the front-end of a cross compiler so that target arithmetic can be correctly</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00065" /><CodeLine lineNumber="65"><Highlight kind="comment">/// performed on the host.  Performance should nonetheless be reasonable,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00066" /><CodeLine lineNumber="66"><Highlight kind="comment">/// particularly for its intended use.  It may be useful as a base</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00067" /><CodeLine lineNumber="67"><Highlight kind="comment">/// implementation for a run-time library during development of a faster</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00068" /><CodeLine lineNumber="68"><Highlight kind="comment">/// target-specific one.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00069" /><CodeLine lineNumber="69"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00070" /><CodeLine lineNumber="70"><Highlight kind="comment">/// All 5 rounding modes in the IEEE-754R draft are handled correctly for all</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00071" /><CodeLine lineNumber="71"><Highlight kind="comment">/// implemented operations.  Currently implemented operations are add, subtract,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00072" /><CodeLine lineNumber="72"><Highlight kind="comment">/// multiply, divide, fused-multiply-add, conversion-to-float,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00073" /><CodeLine lineNumber="73"><Highlight kind="comment">/// conversion-to-integer and conversion-from-integer.  New rounding modes</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00074" /><CodeLine lineNumber="74"><Highlight kind="comment">/// (e.g. away from zero) can be added with three or four lines of code.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00075" /><CodeLine lineNumber="75"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00076" /><CodeLine lineNumber="76"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Four formats are built-in: IEEE single precision, double precision,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00077" /><CodeLine lineNumber="77"><Highlight kind="comment">/// quadruple precision, and x87 80-bit extended double (when operating with</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00078" /><CodeLine lineNumber="78"><Highlight kind="comment">/// full extended precision).  Adding a new format that obeys IEEE semantics</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00079" /><CodeLine lineNumber="79"><Highlight kind="comment">/// only requires adding two lines of code: a declaration and definition of the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00080" /><CodeLine lineNumber="80"><Highlight kind="comment">/// format.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00081" /><CodeLine lineNumber="81"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00082" /><CodeLine lineNumber="82"><Highlight kind="comment">/// All operations return the status of that operation as an exception bit-mask,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00083" /><CodeLine lineNumber="83"><Highlight kind="comment">/// so multiple operations can be done consecutively with their results or-ed</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00084" /><CodeLine lineNumber="84"><Highlight kind="comment">/// together.  The returned status can be useful for compiler diagnostics; e.g.,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00085" /><CodeLine lineNumber="85"><Highlight kind="comment">/// inexact, underflow and overflow can be easily diagnosed on constant folding,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00086" /><CodeLine lineNumber="86"><Highlight kind="comment">/// and compiler optimizers can determine what exceptions would be raised by</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00087" /><CodeLine lineNumber="87"><Highlight kind="comment">/// folding operations and optimize, or perhaps not optimize, accordingly.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00088" /><CodeLine lineNumber="88"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00089" /><CodeLine lineNumber="89"><Highlight kind="comment">/// At present, underflow tininess is detected after rounding; it should be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00090" /><CodeLine lineNumber="90"><Highlight kind="comment">/// straight forward to add support for the before-rounding case too.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00091" /><CodeLine lineNumber="91"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00092" /><CodeLine lineNumber="92"><Highlight kind="comment">/// The library reads hexadecimal floating point numbers as per C99, and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00093" /><CodeLine lineNumber="93"><Highlight kind="comment">/// correctly rounds if necessary according to the specified rounding mode.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00094" /><CodeLine lineNumber="94"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Syntax is required to have been validated by the caller.  It also converts</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00095" /><CodeLine lineNumber="95"><Highlight kind="comment">/// floating point numbers to hexadecimal text as per the C99 %a and %A</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00096" /><CodeLine lineNumber="96"><Highlight kind="comment">/// conversions.  The output precision (or alternatively the natural minimal</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00097" /><CodeLine lineNumber="97"><Highlight kind="comment">/// precision) can be specified; if the requested precision is less than the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00098" /><CodeLine lineNumber="98"><Highlight kind="comment">/// natural precision the output is correctly rounded for the specified rounding</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00099" /><CodeLine lineNumber="99"><Highlight kind="comment">/// mode.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00100" /><CodeLine lineNumber="100"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00101" /><CodeLine lineNumber="101"><Highlight kind="comment">/// It also reads decimal floating point numbers and correctly rounds according</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00102" /><CodeLine lineNumber="102"><Highlight kind="comment">/// to the specified rounding mode.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00103" /><CodeLine lineNumber="103"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00104" /><CodeLine lineNumber="104"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Conversion to decimal text is not currently implemented.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00105" /><CodeLine lineNumber="105"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00106" /><CodeLine lineNumber="106"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Non-zero finite numbers are represented internally as a sign bit, a 16-bit</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00107" /><CodeLine lineNumber="107"><Highlight kind="comment">/// signed exponent, and the significand as an array of integer parts.  After</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00108" /><CodeLine lineNumber="108"><Highlight kind="comment">/// normalization of a number of precision P the exponent is within the range of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00109" /><CodeLine lineNumber="109"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the format, and if the number is not denormal the P-th bit of the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00110" /><CodeLine lineNumber="110"><Highlight kind="comment">/// significand is set as an explicit integer bit.  For denormals the most</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00111" /><CodeLine lineNumber="111"><Highlight kind="comment">/// significant bit is shifted right so that the exponent is maintained at the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00112" /><CodeLine lineNumber="112"><Highlight kind="comment">/// format&#39;s minimum, so that the smallest denormal has just the least</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00113" /><CodeLine lineNumber="113"><Highlight kind="comment">/// significant bit of the significand set.  The sign of zeroes and infinities</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00114" /><CodeLine lineNumber="114"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is significant; the exponent and significand of such numbers is not stored,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00115" /><CodeLine lineNumber="115"><Highlight kind="comment">/// but has a known implicit (deterministic) value: 0 for the significands, 0</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00116" /><CodeLine lineNumber="116"><Highlight kind="comment">/// for zero exponent, all 1 bits for infinity exponent.  For NaNs the sign and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00117" /><CodeLine lineNumber="117"><Highlight kind="comment">/// significand are deterministic, although not really meaningful, and preserved</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00118" /><CodeLine lineNumber="118"><Highlight kind="comment">/// in non-conversion operations.  The exponent is implicitly all 1 bits.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00119" /><CodeLine lineNumber="119"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00120" /><CodeLine lineNumber="120"><Highlight kind="comment">/// APFloat does not provide any exception handling beyond default exception</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00121" /><CodeLine lineNumber="121"><Highlight kind="comment">/// handling. We represent Signaling NaNs via IEEE-754R 2008 6.2.1 should clause</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00122" /><CodeLine lineNumber="122"><Highlight kind="comment">/// by encoding Signaling NaNs with the first bit of its trailing significand as</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00123" /><CodeLine lineNumber="123"><Highlight kind="comment">/// 0</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00124" /><CodeLine lineNumber="124"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00125" /><CodeLine lineNumber="125"><Highlight kind="comment">/// TODO</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00126" /><CodeLine lineNumber="126"><Highlight kind="comment">/// ====</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00127" /><CodeLine lineNumber="127"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00128" /><CodeLine lineNumber="128"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Some features that may or may not be worth adding:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00129" /><CodeLine lineNumber="129"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00130" /><CodeLine lineNumber="130"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Binary to decimal conversion (hard).</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00158" /><CodeLine lineNumber="158"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// The IBM double-double semantics. Such a number consists of a pair of</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00159" /><CodeLine lineNumber="159"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// IEEE 64-bit doubles (Hi, Lo), where |Hi| &gt; |Lo|, and if normal,</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00161" /><CodeLine lineNumber="161"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Therefore it has two 53-bit mantissa parts that aren&#39;t necessarily</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00162" /><CodeLine lineNumber="162"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// adjacent to each other, and two 11-bit exponents.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00163" /><CodeLine lineNumber="163"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00164" /><CodeLine lineNumber="164"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Note: we need to make the value different from semBogus as otherwise</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00167" /><CodeLine lineNumber="167" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52a601f9d15fb988710f86c2481f0982cff"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52a601f9d15fb988710f86c2481f0982cff">S&#95;PPCDoubleDouble</a>,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00168" /><CodeLine lineNumber="168"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// These are legacy semantics for the fallback, inaccurate implementation</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00169" /><CodeLine lineNumber="169"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// of IBM double-double, if the accurate semPPCDoubleDouble doesn&#39;t handle</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00175" /><CodeLine lineNumber="175"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00176" /><CodeLine lineNumber="176"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// 1 + epsilon = 1 + (1 &gt;&gt; 1076)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00177" /><CodeLine lineNumber="177"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00179" /><CodeLine lineNumber="179"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00180" /><CodeLine lineNumber="180"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// Currently, these semantics are used in the following way:</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00182" /><CodeLine lineNumber="182"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//   semPPCDoubleDouble -&gt; (IEEEdouble, IEEEdouble) -&gt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00183" /><CodeLine lineNumber="183"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">//   (64-bit APInt, 64-bit APInt) -&gt; (128-bit APInt) -&gt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00229" /><CodeLine lineNumber="229"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// improved range compared to half (16-bit) formats, at (potentially)</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00230" /><CodeLine lineNumber="230"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// greater throughput than single precision (32-bit) formats.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00231" /><CodeLine lineNumber="231" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52ab04e922575a47a53d1a406925985d5f2"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52ab04e922575a47a53d1a406925985d5f2">S&#95;FloatTF32</a>,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00232" /><CodeLine lineNumber="232"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// 8-bit floating point number with (all the) 8 bits for the exponent</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00233" /><CodeLine lineNumber="233"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// like in FP32. There are no zeroes, no infinities, and no denormal values.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00234" /><CodeLine lineNumber="234"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// This format has unsigned representation only. (U -&gt; Unsigned only).</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00235" /><CodeLine lineNumber="235"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// NaN is represented with all bits set to 1 Bias is 127</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00236" /><CodeLine lineNumber="236"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// This format represents the scale data type in the MX specification from:</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00237" /><CodeLine lineNumber="237"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// https://www.opencompute.org/documents/ocp-microscaling-formats-mx-v1-0-spec-final-pdf</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00238" /><CodeLine lineNumber="238" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52af9c857c44bca65044d0582c1aa608f01"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52af9c857c44bca65044d0582c1aa608f01">S&#95;Float8E8M0FNU</a>,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00239" /><CodeLine lineNumber="239"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// 6-bit floating point number with bit layout S1E3M2. Unlike IEEE-754</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00240" /><CodeLine lineNumber="240"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// types, there are no infinity or NaN values. The format is detailed in</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00241" /><CodeLine lineNumber="241"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// https://www.opencompute.org/documents/ocp-microscaling-formats-mx-v1-0-spec-final-pdf</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00242" /><CodeLine lineNumber="242" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52a99773cadb5a3e21af5ad411ff0d56bcf"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52a99773cadb5a3e21af5ad411ff0d56bcf">S&#95;Float6E3M2FN</a>,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00243" /><CodeLine lineNumber="243"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// 6-bit floating point number with bit layout S1E2M3. Unlike IEEE-754</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00244" /><CodeLine lineNumber="244"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// types, there are no infinity or NaN values. The format is detailed in</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00245" /><CodeLine lineNumber="245"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// https://www.opencompute.org/documents/ocp-microscaling-formats-mx-v1-0-spec-final-pdf</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00246" /><CodeLine lineNumber="246" lineLink="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52a17d727cd884fae7f7f3f1b3e029ac575"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/apfloatbase/#ae28d826c1042631ac188d8295949ff52a17d727cd884fae7f7f3f1b3e029ac575">S&#95;Float6E2M3FN</a>,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00247" /><CodeLine lineNumber="247"><Highlight kind="normal">    </Highlight><Highlight kind="comment">// 4-bit floating point number with bit layout S1E2M1. Unlike IEEE-754</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00559" /><CodeLine lineNumber="559"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Overload to compute a hash code for an APFloat value.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00560" /><CodeLine lineNumber="560"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00561" /><CodeLine lineNumber="561"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Note that the use of hash codes for floating point values is in general</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00562" /><CodeLine lineNumber="562"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// frought with peril. Equality is hard to define for these values. For</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00563" /><CodeLine lineNumber="563"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// example, should negative and positive zero hash to different codes? Are</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00564" /><CodeLine lineNumber="564"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// they equal or not? This hash value implementation specifically</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00565" /><CodeLine lineNumber="565"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// emphasizes producing different codes for different inputs in order to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00566" /><CodeLine lineNumber="566"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// be used in canonicalization and memoization. As such, equality is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00567" /><CodeLine lineNumber="567"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// bitwiseIsEqual, and 0 != 0</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00568" /><CodeLine lineNumber="568"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">friend</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/hash-code">hash&#95;code</a> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/detail/ieeefloat/#a87ec5cfce4a8b6896193c822f2dc5894">hash&#95;value</a>(</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">const</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/detail/ieeefloat">IEEEFloat</a> &amp;Arg);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00569" /><CodeLine lineNumber="569"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00570" /><CodeLine lineNumber="570"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Converts this value into a decimal string.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00571" /><CodeLine lineNumber="571"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00572" /><CodeLine lineNumber="572"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// \\param FormatPrecision The maximum number of digits of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00573" /><CodeLine lineNumber="573"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   precision to output.  If there are fewer digits available,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00574" /><CodeLine lineNumber="574"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   zero padding will not be used unless the value is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00575" /><CodeLine lineNumber="575"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   integral and small enough to be expressed in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00576" /><CodeLine lineNumber="576"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   FormatPrecision digits.  0 means to use the natural</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00577" /><CodeLine lineNumber="577"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   precision of the number.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00578" /><CodeLine lineNumber="578"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// \\param FormatMaxPadding The maximum number of zeros to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00579" /><CodeLine lineNumber="579"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   consider inserting before falling back to scientific</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00580" /><CodeLine lineNumber="580"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   notation.  0 means to always use scientific notation.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00581" /><CodeLine lineNumber="581"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00582" /><CodeLine lineNumber="582"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// \\param TruncateZero Indicate whether to remove the trailing zero in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00583" /><CodeLine lineNumber="583"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   fraction part or not. Also setting this parameter to false forcing</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00584" /><CodeLine lineNumber="584"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   producing of output more similar to default printf behavior.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00585" /><CodeLine lineNumber="585"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   Specifically the lower e is used as exponent delimiter and exponent</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00586" /><CodeLine lineNumber="586"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   always contains no less than two digits.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00587" /><CodeLine lineNumber="587"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00588" /><CodeLine lineNumber="588"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Number       Precision    MaxPadding      Result</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00589" /><CodeLine lineNumber="589"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// ------       ---------    ----------      ------</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00590" /><CodeLine lineNumber="590"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// 10100              5             2       10100</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00591" /><CodeLine lineNumber="591"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// 10100              4             2       10100</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00592" /><CodeLine lineNumber="592"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// 10100              5             1       10100</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00593" /><CodeLine lineNumber="593"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// 0.0101              5             2       0.0101</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00594" /><CodeLine lineNumber="594"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// 0.0101              4             2       0.0101</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00595" /><CodeLine lineNumber="595"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// 0.0101              4             1       0.0101</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00614" /><CodeLine lineNumber="614"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00615" /><CodeLine lineNumber="615"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Returns the exponent of the internal representation of the APFloat.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00616" /><CodeLine lineNumber="616"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00617" /><CodeLine lineNumber="617"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Because the radix of APFloat is 2, this is equivalent to floor(log2(x)).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00618" /><CodeLine lineNumber="618"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// For special APFloat values, this returns special error codes:</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00619" /><CodeLine lineNumber="619"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00620" /><CodeLine lineNumber="620"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   NaN -&gt; \\c IEK&#95;NaN</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00621" /><CodeLine lineNumber="621"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///   0   -&gt; \\c IEK&#95;Zero</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01423" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1423"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// As such, this method can be used to do an exact bit-for-bit comparison of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01424" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1424"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// two floating point values.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01425" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1425"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01426" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1426"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// We leave the version with the double argument here because it&#39;s just so</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01427" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1427"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// convenient to write &quot;2.0&quot; and the like.  Without this function we&#39;d</Highlight></CodeLine>
